specs.rs is the entire checks/ subtree — no other files, no submodules. It exists as the single source of truth for what checkpoint verification runs and how each tool's output is turned into diagnostics.

Anything upstream that needs to run or interpret a check goes through `SPECS` and `Spec::name` string keys; there is no other indexing scheme, so adding, renaming, or removing a check here is a breaking change to every caller that matches on those name strings (notably `regen_command`, and any reporting code keyed by name elsewhere in ctx-verify). Order in `SPECS` is meaningful — `fmt` must stay first since it mutates the tree before the read-only checks run.

The four parser flavors are the only diagnostic-shaping logic in the subtree; a new check must reuse one of them (compiler_parser, script_parser, noop_parser, test_parser) or extend this file with a fifth — there's no separate parsing module to touch. `regen_command`'s two-entry allowlist (contracts, architecture) is a deliberate ADR-022 constraint, not an oversight, so extending auto-fix to a new check requires checking that ADR first, not just adding a match arm.

No intent.md exists to check divergence against.